He has increased tone in his lower limbs with sustained clonus at the ankles bilaterally. He requires a wheelchair for mobility.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following interventions is most appropriate to reduce this child\u0027s lower limb spasticity?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Botulinum toxin injections","Oral diazepam","Selective dorsal rhizotomy","Hyperbaric oxygen therapy","Constraint-induced movement therapy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBotulinum toxin injections\u003C/strong\u003E are an effective treatment for reducing focal spasticity in children with cerebral palsy. The toxin works by temporarily blocking the release of acetylcholine at the neuromuscular junction, leading to muscle relaxation. In this child with spastic diplegia, injections into the gastrocnemius and soleus muscles could help reduce ankle clonus and improve range of motion. The effects typically last 3-6 months before the injections need to be repeated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral diazepam\u003C/strong\u003E is a long-acting benzodiazepine that can reduce generalized spasticity. However, it often causes sedation and is not as effective as targeted botulinum toxin injections for treating focal spasticity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelective dorsal rhizotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is a neurosurgical procedure that involves cutting selected sensory nerve roots to reduce spasticity. It is reserved for children with severe lower limb spasticity who have not responded to more conservative measures. This child may be a candidate in the future if his spasticity cannot be adequately controlled with medications and injections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no evidence to support the use of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehyperbaric oxygen therapy\u003C/strong\u003E for reducing spasticity in cerebral palsy. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConstraint-induced movement therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is used to improve upper limb function in hemiplegic cerebral palsy and would not be indicated for this child with lower limb spasticity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Botulinum toxin injections can help reduce focal spasticity in children with cerebral palsy.","Botulinum toxin is most effective when combined with intensive physiotherapy and occupational therapy.","The effects of botulinum toxin are temporary and injections need to be repeated every 3-6 months."],"references":["Barkoudah E. Cerebral palsy: Overview of management and prognosis. In: UpToDate [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/cerebral-palsy-overview-of-management-and-prognosis","Shamsoddini A, Amirsalari S, Hollisaz MT, Rahimnia A, Khatibi-Aghda A. Management of spasticity in children with cerebral palsy. Iran J Pediatr. 2014 Aug;24(4):345-51. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4339555/","Cerebral palsy. In: Royal Children\u0027s Hospital clinical practice guidelines [online]. Accessed 2024. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Cerebral_palsy/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33474"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13749"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33474"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-13T20:32:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-03T17:06:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6368"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48552"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"